<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by the Nisai Group</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Written evidence submitted by the Nisai Group</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Issues and concerns raised in the Annual Report relating to the performance of local authorities in child protection and services for looked-after children</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are many positive commitments to ensuring that local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">authorities provide the best services for looked after children in the Annual Report.  However, there are still some issues that need addressing including:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“Where local authorities are failing… (there is) a lack of understanding about what constitutes good</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> practice”;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“Social care only succeeds where it sees and hears children, understands their potential and the stresses that they face… Where a child has already suffered .. before services have intervened, what represents progress will be very personal to t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hem’”; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> “At age 11, half of looked after children do not reach the expected level in English and mathematics”</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In addition, over </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">10% of children are still being moved more than three times a year</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ore than half only given a week's notice or les</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s of being moved to another foster home and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a quarter given no notice at all. This</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> does </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not provide a stable context for learning</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">requent relocation ranks as poor practice by an authority that neither understands a child’s needs, nor changes their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">educational prognosis.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This need not be the case. Ofsted’s report also states that better authorities “had robust data systems that enabled virtual schools to monitor and track the progress of children, individually as well as collectively” as well as add</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ress specific educational issues through the use of technology.  This means there is support for its wider use in the education of looked after children - a sensible position as technology: </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 17pt 0pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">helps alleviate the disruptive effects that rapid and/or frequent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> placement changes impose on the child/young person;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 17pt 0pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">delivers education, even when children are waiting for a new school place after a change in placement, as it is delivered remotely; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 17pt 0pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">saves the Government money because technology enables traditionally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> home-schooled students to enter an online classroom with 10 other students reducing the overall salary bill.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 17pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One example of an online education provider is The Nisai Virtual Academy (NVA).  It is </span><span style="color:#252f36; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an award winning online learning community</span><span style="color:#252f36; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, on a secure e</span><span style="color:#252f36; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ncrypted platform that provides a </span><span style="color:#252f36; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">real-time teaching environment</span><span style="color:#252f36; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with CRB checked specialist teachers</span><span style="color:#252f36; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="color:#252f36; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that specialise</span><span style="color:#252f36; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in </span><span style="color:#252f36; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SEN and </span><span style="color:#252f36; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">personalised learning</span><span style="color:#252f36; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In addition, it provides a secure reporting system that keeps the virtual head informed of attendance, contribution and behaviour meaning that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">those who are excluded from traditional education</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> can </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">access full and proper education online.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 17pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Each learner has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">their own personal profile based on their ability and the subjects that they want to study.  It </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">allows</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> students to engage in live lessons with teachers and other students as well as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> providing a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">well being centre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to help reduce barriers to learning</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  Indeed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the results speak for themselves. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he students who use the NVA are often those who, in the eyes of the majority, are unlikely to gain any qualifications and/or achieve anything with their lives.  Considering that a quarter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of looked-after </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">children still </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">obtain no qualifications with a further quarter obtaining fewer than five GCSEs or equivalent, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">they can be easily placed in this category. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, last year 91% of the students of Nisai Learning achieved GCSE and A-level qualifications, and 30.6% achieved</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> A* to C grades – a figure below the national average but again, considering many of these students would have had no GCSE or A-levels under their belts without the use of the online education, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">this is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an impressive achievement. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With this in mind, action</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> needs to be taken to:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ensure the Government understands that alternative education can play a part in the education for looked-after children;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Develop a link between alternative providers and local authorities to ensure that young people in care are given</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the option of online education if they are outside the mainstream system.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Issues and concerns raised in the Annual Report relating to the performance of secure accommodation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The report states that “28% of young people in secure children’s homes were neg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ative about the support they receive with their work or education”.  A terrifying statistic backed up by previous reports that:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">73% of young offenders describe their education as ‘nil’</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">60% of offenders in prison are functionally illiterate and innume</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rate</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Education is one of the key elements to a young person being able to leave a life of crime behind. However, many offenders in custody are unable to access traditional education; and for that reason online education provision can help these young pe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ople.   Indeed, many young offenders have experienced ‘disrupted education’ in the mainstream system and this often continues once they are in a secure location.   Providing them with access to online learning tools like the Nisai Virtual Academy, would ov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ercome this problem, as they would be able to study from any location, provided they have access to a PC or laptop with a broadband Internet connection. Not only will this provide continuity in their learning whilst they are in custody, but would enable th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">em to continue their studies without interruption once they complete their custodial sentence. Latest figures show there were “just 119 GCSE passes in public sector young offender institutions in 2010/11, the latest year for which figures are available. Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is represents a 49 per cent drop on the number of passes for 2009/10, when the figure stood at 232…”</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The opportunity to study in a consistent manner will not only give young offenders the best chance to succeed, but will also support their resettlement an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d enhance their ability to re-engage with education, training and employment.  It will also mean that young people can engage with the education system without feeling that they are dealing with the “authorities” with whom they may have trust issues becaus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e of previous treatment or experiences.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With this in mind action needs to be taken to:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ensure that the Government understands that alternative education can play a part in the education for young offenders and includes this in its plan to help educate y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oung offenders whether they have short or long sentences; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Develop a list of alternative providers through a stringent procurement process that can provide education to young people within secure locations</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p>